Detailed Architecture: Chunking and Embedding Pipeline

1) Purpose

Define a robust, repeatable, and incremental chunking/embedding architecture for the in-scope Groww scheme links so retrieval remains factual, precise, and citation-safe.

Primary goals:
- Preserve factual fields accurately (expense_ratio, exit_load, min_sip, benchmark, etc.)
- Produce semantically coherent chunks for high retrieval quality
- Support incremental refresh (reprocess only changed pages)
- Maintain strict traceability from chunk to source URL for one-link citation enforcement

2) Inputs and Outputs

2.1 Inputs
- Canonical URL list (7 in-scope Groww links)
- Parsed/normalized page text from scraping service
- Source metadata:
  - source_url
  - crawl_date
  - optional extracted page-level last_updated_text

2.2 Outputs
- Versioned chunk dataset
- Embedding vectors for each active chunk (1024-dim, L2-normalized)
- Vector index (ChromaDB persistent collection, cosine similarity)
- Chunk-to-source mapping table (chunk_map.json)
- Pipeline run report (counts, changed pages, failures)

3) Pipeline Stages

Raw HTML
  -> Clean text blocks
  -> Structural segmentation         [Stage A]
  -> Field-aware chunking            [Stage B]
  -> Chunk metadata enrichment       [Stage C]
  -> Chunk hashing/versioning        [Stage D]
  -> Embedding generation            [Stage E]
  -> Vector upsert + deactivation    [Stage F]
  -> Retrieval-ready index

4) Stage A: Structural Segmentation

Before chunking, split page text into semantic blocks:
- header_block: scheme name/category snapshot
- facts_block: expense ratio, AUM, NAV-like factual fields
- fees_block: exit load, minimum investment/SIP
- risk_benchmark_block: riskometer, benchmark
- process_block: statement/tax/capital gains workflow references (if present)
- other_block: residual useful content

Segmentation rules:
- Use heading-based boundaries where possible.
- Preserve bullet/table row adjacency so label-value pairs stay together.
- Drop repetitive boilerplate text (footer/legal nav repeats).

Rationale:
- Prevent splitting fact label and value across unrelated chunks.

5) Stage B: Field-Aware Chunking

5.1 Chunk Unit Strategy
- Preferred unit: semantic paragraph/table-group, not fixed length first.
- Fallback to length-based split only when a unit exceeds threshold.

5.2 Chunk Size Policy
- Target: 650 characters
- Min: 350 characters (guideline, not hard-enforced)
- Max hard cap: 1000 characters
- Overlap: 100 characters

Why:
- Smaller chunks improve precision.
- Moderate overlap protects facts near boundaries.

5.3 Rules for Financial Facts
- Keep label + value + qualifier in same chunk whenever possible.
  Example: "Exit load: 1% if redeemed within 365 days"
- Do not split numeric tokens from units (%, days, INR).
- If a field appears in multiple sections, retain both chunks but set metadata priority.

5.4 Table/Key-Value Handling
- Convert table rows to normalized lines:
  Field: Value (Context)
- Group related rows into the same chunk up to max size.
- If table is long, split by logical subgroups, not arbitrary row count.

6) Stage C: Metadata Enrichment

Attach rich metadata to every chunk:
- chunk_id (stable UUID v5, deterministic from source_url + text)
- source_url
- source_domain = groww.in
- document_type = scheme_page_html
- scheme_name
- field_type (one primary + optional secondary list)
- field_types (all matched labels)
- section_name
- crawl_date
- last_updated_text (if available)
- chunk_version
- content_hash
- is_active (boolean)
- char_count

Field type classification:
- Rule-based mapping from section labels/keywords (checked in priority order):
  - expense ratio -> expense_ratio
  - exit load -> exit_load
  - minimum + sip -> min_sip
  - riskometer -> riskometer
  - benchmark -> benchmark
  - lock-in -> lock_in
  - statement/tax/capital gains -> statement_process

7) Stage D: Versioning and Change Detection

Versioning model:
- Compute page_hash from normalized full page text.
- Compute content_hash from normalized chunk text.

Incremental behavior:
- If page_hash unchanged: skip re-chunking and re-embedding.
- If changed:
  - Regenerate chunks for that page.
  - Compare new content_hash values with active version.
  - Upsert new/changed chunks only.
  - Mark removed old chunks as is_active = false.

Benefits:
- Lower embedding cost (local model is fast; still avoids redundant work)
- Faster daily refresh
- Clean rollback and auditability

8) Stage E: Embedding Generation

8.1 Embedding Model

Selected model : BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5
Library        : sentence-transformers (local inference, no API key required)
Dimension      : 1024
Normalization  : L2-normalize all vectors (enables cosine similarity via dot product)
Instruction    : none for document chunks; queries prepend
                 "Represent this question for searching relevant passages: {query}"

Rationale for BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5:
- Top-tier MTEB retrieval benchmark performance for English text
- 1024-dim dense vectors: high discriminability for short factual passages
- Strong numeric-token handling (%, INR amounts, day counts) critical for fund data
- Fully local — zero API cost, no rate limit, no key rotation needed
- Deterministic: identical text always produces identical vector
- Model version pinned in config (EMBED_MODEL); full corpus re-embedded only on upgrade

Model policy:
- Keep one production model version pinned in config.py: EMBED_MODEL = "BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5"
- Only re-embed full corpus when EMBED_MODEL value changes.

8.2 Embedding Preprocessing
- Normalize whitespace (handled automatically by sentence-transformers tokenizer)
- Preserve punctuation that changes meaning (%, /, -)
- Do not pre-lowercase — the model's WordPiece tokenizer handles casing
- Keep original text separately in chunk record for answer grounding

8.3 Embedding Batch Strategy
- Batch size: 32 (balances RAM and throughput; ~85 total chunks fits in one pass)
- Retry failed items with exponential backoff
- Persist embed_state.json after each batch: maps chunk_id -> content_hash
- Incremental skip: if content_hash matches cached record, reuse stored vector

8.4 Embedding Record Schema (data/embeddings/{fund_slug}.jsonl, one record per line)
- chunk_id
- source_url
- scheme_name
- section_name
- field_type
- text (original, unmodified)
- embedding_vector (list[float], len=1024)
- embedding_model = "BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5"
- embedding_dim = 1024
- embedded_at (ISO-8601 UTC timestamp)
- content_hash (hex SHA-256 of chunk text — used for incremental skip logic)

9) Stage F: Vector Index Upsert

9.1 Vector Store Selection

Selected store : Chroma Cloud (https://www.trychroma.com) — fully managed, hosted
Client         : chromadb.CloudClient(tenant, database, api_key)
Host           : api.trychroma.com  (HTTPS, port 443)
Collection     : "mutual_fund_chunks"  (single collection for all 7 funds)
Distance       : cosine

Rationale:
- Fully managed cloud: no local index files, no disk quota concerns, accessible from any environment
- CloudClient handles auth, TLS, and connection pooling — minimal config surface
- Same ChromaDB Python API as local client: identical upsert/query interface
- Native metadata filtering: where= clauses on scheme_name, field_type, section_name, crawl_date
- Idempotent upsert by chunk_id: re-running Stage F on unchanged chunks is a no-op
- Stores text, embedding vector, and metadata together — one query call returns everything the retriever needs
- Cosine distance metric aligns with L2-normalised bge-large vectors

Required environment secrets (stored in Replit Secrets, never hardcoded):
- CHROMA_API_KEY  : API key from Chroma Cloud console (https://app.trychroma.com)
- CHROMA_TENANT   : tenant ID shown in Chroma Cloud console
- CHROMA_DATABASE : database name created in Chroma Cloud console

9.2 Chroma Cloud Document Schema (one document per chunk)
- id          : chunk_id (UUID v5 string — stable across runs, used for upsert)
- embedding   : list[float] len=1024, L2-normalised bge-large-en-v1.5 vector
- document    : chunk text (for context assembly and answer grounding)
- metadata    :
    source_url       : str
    scheme_name      : str
    section_name     : str  (e.g. "fees_block")
    field_type       : str  (e.g. "expense_ratio")
    crawl_date       : str  (ISO date)
    content_hash     : str  (hex SHA-256, for change detection)
    embedding_model  : str  ("BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5")
    embedded_at      : str  (ISO-8601 UTC)

9.3 Index Write Strategy
- Instantiate CloudClient using CHROMA_API_KEY, CHROMA_TENANT, CHROMA_DATABASE from env.
- Get or create collection "mutual_fund_chunks" with cosine distance.
- For each changed slug (from Stage E): read its embeddings JSONL and upsert to cloud collection.
- Upsert is idempotent: same chunk_id with same content is overwritten in-place.
- Run 3-probe retrieval sanity check (expense ratio / min SIP / exit load) after upsert.
- On connection failure: log error, retain previous cloud data, surface failure to caller.

Upsert constraints:
- Only active chunks (is_active = true) are upserted.
- chunk_id is the stable document ID — provides citation traceability chunk -> source_url.
- Metadata fields available as cloud query-time filters: scheme_name, field_type.

10) Retrieval Alignment Requirements

Chunking/embedding must support downstream retriever behavior:
- Metadata filter first (scheme_name, then field_type)
- Similarity search second (ChromaDB cosine similarity with L2-normalized bge-large vectors)
- Optional re-rank on numeric/entity overlap

Query-time instruction:
- Prefix user query with "Represent this question for searching relevant passages: {query}"
  before encoding with BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5 for retrieval.

Quality rule:
- For top factual queries, top-3 retrieved chunks should contain exact field answer in at least one chunk.

11) Quality Gates

Run quality checks after each scheduled pipeline execution:

Chunk integrity checks:
- No empty chunks
- No duplicate active chunk IDs
- No missing source_url or scheme_name

Embedding checks:
- Vector dimension = 1024 for every record
- No NaN/inf values
- Embedding count matches active chunk count

Retrieval smoke set:
- Fixed benchmark queries (expense ratio, exit load, min SIP, benchmark, riskometer)
- Ensure at least one expected source chunk appears in top-k

Citation traceability:
- Every retrievable chunk maps to exactly one valid in-scope URL

12) Failure and Recovery

Failure categories:
- Scrape parse failure
- Chunking transform failure
- Embedding model load failure
- Index validation failure

Recovery strategy:
- Fail closed (keep previous active index)
- Emit run status and failed URL/chunk IDs
- Retry once for transient failures
- Manual re-run command for targeted URLs

13) Operational Integration with GitHub Actions

Daily workflow (9:20 schedule) invokes:
- python -m ingestion.run_ingestion           (scrape + segment + chunk)
- python -m ingestion.run_embedding           (Stage E: embed changed chunks)
- python -m ingestion.run_index_upsert        (Stage F: upsert to ChromaDB collection)
- python -m ingestion.run_quality_checks      (validate index + smoke retrieval)

If all checks pass:
- Publish/swap active index artifacts

If any check fails:
- Do not swap index
- Mark workflow failed and notify

